brad@clarinet.com (Brad Templeton) writes:

>Not to mention the fact that as long as those who use non-skipjack encryption,
>while it remains legal, may become automatic suspects.   If those who use
>other encryption become a small minority, I can even see, "He refused to
>use skipjack" introduced as cirmustantial evidence in a court case.

>Most of us see the flaw in this sort of "Honest people have nothing to hide"
>argument.  But do judges and juries?

>What happens when the predominant non-users of skipjack are the mob,
>terrorists, religious cults and us, the "privacy freaks."

>Won't it be easy to push through congress to ban it?  Or won't we look a lot
>more suspect hanging with that crowd of professional criminals and
>troublemakers?

My question is:  How will they *know* that people aren't using skipjack?
Without benefit of a warrant to (try to) decode the information.

You can always pre-encrypt too... possibly even hiding the real info in
a mass of worthless data...  There'd be absolutely no way of catching you.


Pat
